values.QID1_TEXT: Falling in love with someone else when I was married to another person.
Not taking a timeout to spend time with the important people in my life. I have had a tendency to place work responsibilities ahead of my family and others.
Not fully appreciating and enjoying the period of life when my children were young.
Not studying abroad in college
I did not persist at university and in early adulthood with creative writing
Letting someone else take the blame for my wrongdoing
Not visiting my parents/grandparents more when they were alive.
Not taking more chances.

I regret being constantly over-committed during my working years, being too busy to spend time at home with my family and generally enjoy life and health. I think it was a way to avoid being responsible for my choices. Now that I'm retired, I'm going slower and enjoying life more, but it is hard to overcome life-long habits.
I didn't learn to speak fluently in another language
Automatically doing what I thought was expected of me, rather than considering what I actually needed to feel happy and fulfilled.
Not spending more time with my near-death mother when she was in the hospital.
Not spending enough time with my parents when I was in my 30s.
I regret not learning how to seek help sooner
I wish I had been more willing to fail; that is, I wish I had been bolder in engaging in situations where I was not likely to succeed, for the sake of learning from the experience.
I majored in Business for a secure job instead of the English I loved.
Not consistently following my heart over my mind in some career decisions.

Once, as a child, I made an innocently intended remark that I MUCH later realized must have been extremely hurtful to my Mother. I regret that I made the remark, and also that I never found a way to apologize that wouldn't have made things worse by bringing it up.
I have never studied  abroad only in Germany. I had the chance but was too shy to go for it.
I should have had therapy sooner
I didn't take my wife's mental health issues more seriously before we had children.
That I didn't go to film school.
Not quitting that job sooner
Not taking more risks earlier in life - exploring the world, meeting more people, following my heart into adventures that didn't "fit the box".

I regret not having focused my career on one rather obscure topic that I was passionate about and could become a serious expert in over 30 years such that I could feel my expertise is really valuable at the end of my career and would give me as sense of being in demand even as I pass traditional retirement age.
Not joining the military. I could have served my country more in a life of active service. I finally came to government service and love my work. I wish I'd started earlier.
I wish I had been more adventurous when I was a young adult, and been more confident - maybe traveled or studied abroad.
Believing the world lives by my standards.
Not dealing with my eating disorder sooner.
Abandoning good friends
Trying to be perfect!
Gaining weight, a few pounds a year, through my life.
Being concerned about what others think of me.
I wish I had not had a boyfriend through college who monopolized my time and I had met more great people.  I went to an amazing university!!
I did not take financial risks that would have made me more money when I could afford to take the risk (i.e., invest in real estate). I played it safe and now I am still scraping by.
Wish I would have committed to my now wife earlier. Life has been so much better since.
Not taking bold chances early enough in life
Starting saving and financial planning sooner
Focusing on work more than on people. From missing family events to avoiding work network opportunities.
Living a life for God sooner. Putting others and my goals before God’s plan for me.
I sacrificed family time for work time.
Infidelity in my relationship prior to our marriage
I havent yet published a book. I havent even written a full manuscript.
I regret that I have not honored a commitment to a friend, which led to me not having contact with him anymore.
Not being brave enough to have a child through adoption or artificial insemination.
Not being bolder - I didn't realize how much growing up poor limited what I thought was possible for myself and people like me.
That I spent much too long planning to do things instead of getting up and doing them.
As a child, how I took my frustrations out on my horse - the pain I caused my horse who I considered my best friend.

I was mean to my mom during a speech at my wedding (I was 36 when I got married.) It was totally ungracious and unwarranted, and was probably a result of exhaustion, alcohol and stress. But I felt horrible about it that night and ever since.
That I didn’t have people over more often for dinner and host more parties.
Not promoting myself more in my career.  Allowed others to take credit for my work.
I haven't travelled more
I regret not standing up for myself in the workplace — fair pay, respect, advancement opportunity.
Not picking a professional career path earlier in life, and going straight into the workforce without a college degree.
I regret that I have not been more patient in my dealings with others.
Waiting too long to move from my past employer.  I was there 20 years and should have moved on sooner.

I regret not sitting for the CPA exam right after graduation. I should have thought farther ahead and imagined my career 10 years down the road and the flexibility that the CPA credential would provide.
Believing knew everything and ignoring the wisdom of elders.
Should have been bold enough to say 'No' to things that were abusive to self.
That I wasn’t smarter about money management and investing at an earlier age.

Not telling my dad, while he was still well, how much I appreciated all the sacrifices he made for us in his life choices and his work. (I was 20 when he died, so I wasn't a fully-formed and conscientious adult yet, so I don't blame myself too badly.)
Not letting go of people who created a negative environment for me. Always trying to empathise and keep my bridges has also robbed me of confidence.
Not taking charge of my healthy habits sooner in life
Too much drinking and too many boyfriends in between ages of 19-24
The business I started that later failed. I’m still paying off the debt. Maybe I won’t regret it so much when the debt is gone.
Not working to my potential in college

Not having more direct conversations with my spouse before we got married about what we ultimately wanted in our lives (i.e., where we wanted to live, how important stability is vs. pursuing our dreams, etc.). He's the greatest, so I'd definitely still marry him if I had it all to do over again. But it would have set the tone from "day one" about how we communicate as a couple and saved us some heartache/conflict down the line.
My biggest regret would be not pursuing a degree in biology because I was told it would not be a lucrative profession.
Caring too much about what other people thought and holding myself back from doing things I would have enjoyed.

As a 17 year old I was on my way trying to become an Olympic athlete in cycling.  My coach was well placed to get me there but I lacked the drive and will to make it happen.  Although I was a champion locally, I failed to get to the next level and looking back on it, I know it was because I chose fun and games (partying) over the sacrifice that was required to get to the Olympics.
That I did not find a partner.  And equally important that I didn't see how being in a partnership could make me a better person.
Not taking more vacations/trips with the kids. Too much time was spent with organized sports activities.
Not being a more present father when my son was younger. Trying to be more of a mentor now that he is in his late 20's.
That I didn't leave an abusive relationship sooner.
Worrying about others opinions of me in high school and throughout my twenties and trying to conform to them
Not spending more time with my parents in their later years, before they died -- which would have meant spending more time with the rest of my family, too, some of whom are also gone now.
not finishing college

The way I treated one of my older sisters. I criticized her often, tattled on her and bossed her around. All around unkind to her. I blamed her for our bad relationship, but as I adult, I saw how I contributed to the problems we had. I apologized about 3 years ago. She and I do not have many things in common, but we are kind to one another. She's one of the most thoughtful people in my life. I can't imagine not having her as my sister.
I wasn’t as empathetic as I could have been towards my now deceased wife
That I didn't encourage my son to play and explore outside more, and learn to practical things.
Not doing more with my children.
I regret getting married young and having a baby instead of finishing college.
I regret never having learned to trust someone unconditionally but to always fear to get hurt.
Drinking too much during college and not focusing enough on developing my talents
I regret not selecting a career that is exciting to me rather than based on practicality and compensation.
Not dancing with my grandmom at an event when I was a kid
I wish I hadn't gotten married so young, and allowed myself to compromise my values for the sake of a man.
I wish I had considered and helped others more. In other words, I regret being too self-centered.
I regret that we did not practice more (nonreligious) traditions with our kids (21, 25). We did do some things routinely - summer lake trips, etc.), but I wish we'd done many more. Sigh.
Not entering a Cher look-alike contest in the 1970s.
Not trying harder to change my career in my mid 30's to early 40's.
That I haven't been as involved in my church family as I would like to have been.
That I didn’t take the opportunity to ask people more about their lives.     I read an obituary and learn such interesting things about them that I never knew.

Not saving more when I was a young adult, not being nicer to people when I was a teenager. 

That is 2, sorry
Not taking more chances because I was afraid of looking like a failure

I regret listening to my mother instead of listening to myself regarding pretty much everything - but specifically listening to her regarding my major life decisions... college choice, college major, marriage.
I regret not handling relationship breakups that I initiated more thoughtfully.

The most significant regret I have (though there certainly are others) is how horribly I treated a classmate back in grade school. I'm not sure why we teased her so much. She wasn't a rocket scientist, but she wasn't a bad person. I went along with the crowd, which is not typical of me overall. I'm very ashamed how I gave in to group-think and that this poor girl suffered for it. I should have stood up for her. I often wonder what became of her, and I sincerely hope she rose above the rest of us. She deserves that.
I didn't get into a regular habit of saving more money throughout my life and take better advantage of compound interest.
Not taking a promotion with a better company for less money. Instead I moved to a horribly lead company for more money.
Not having children.
I regret being a verbal bully to my classmates in middle school. As I approach my 40th high school reunion next month I see the long-term, permanent effects of my words and actions.
Not being nicer to my parents.
Not marrying the man I loved because of my family's opinion. He died in a car crash in 1994 when we had just reconnected. To be Loved and Happiness trumps all other endeavours.
I regret not moving my body more: exercising, hiking, dancing, sitting less in general...when I was younger.

Not considering other career choices.  I decided I was going to be a lawyer around 8 years old.  That's what I did.  I had no idea what being a lawyer meant, nor did I consider any alternative possibility.
Choosing the wrong major in college because I listened to what other people told me instead of knowing myself.
Changing my last name when I got married.

I didn't talk to my father more before he passed away.  I could have learned more about our family history, why he opened a business, how dealt with hard times, and made sure I understood his legacy so I could help keep it alive.
I have spent my entire adult life overweight. I feel well and feel active but I am sure it has impacted what people think of me.
Not connecting more with my co-workers
I regret that I was not bolder about love when I was younger, that I held myself back out of fear.
The way I broke up with a long-time girlfriend years ago (25+ years ago)
Not speaking up sooner & louder about the sexual abuse I experienced.
Giving my father a hard time when I was a kid. Only started to have a better relationship with him as a later teenager.
Getting married so young before dating more.
Going straight into work after leaving University and not having too much fun. I have no stories!
I regret not committing to my physical and mental fitness. It means I have way less energy and strength than I could have.
Not studying hard enough
Worrying too much about what other people think of me.
